# .clang-tidy — clang-tidy configuration (STRICT)
#
# Reference: https://clang.llvm.org/extra/clang-tidy/checks/list.html
# Run manually:           clang-tidy path/to/file.cpp -p build/debug
# Run on every build:     set CMAKE_CXX_CLANG_TIDY (slower; can also be wired
#                         in CMakePresets via cacheVariables).
#
# Philosophy
# ----------
# This is the strict end of the dial. The premise: a learning project benefits
# more from clang-tidy yelling about a real C++ idiom than from silence about
# a pattern that "works." False positives are the price of admission — when one
# fires on code you've decided is correct, silence it at the call site:
#
#     // NOLINTNEXTLINE(check-name)  -- reason
#     auto* p = some_legacy_api();
#
# Prefer NOLINT over disabling a check globally. The point is to be forced to
# justify each escape.
#
# How the Checks string works
# ---------------------------
# Comma-separated list, evaluated in order:
#   '-*'                 disable everything
#   'group-*'            enable a whole group
#   '-group-some-check'  surgically disable a single check
#
# Ordering matters: enable broadly, then subtract specific known-noisy items.

Checks: >
  -*,
  bugprone-*,
  clang-analyzer-*,
  concurrency-*,
  cppcoreguidelines-*,
  misc-*,
  modernize-*,
  performance-*,
  portability-*,
  readability-*,
  -bugprone-easily-swappable-parameters,
  -cppcoreguidelines-avoid-magic-numbers,
  -cppcoreguidelines-non-private-member-variables-in-classes,
  -cppcoreguidelines-pro-bounds-array-to-pointer-decay,
  -cppcoreguidelines-pro-bounds-pointer-arithmetic,
  -misc-non-private-member-variables-in-classes,
  -misc-no-recursion,
  -modernize-use-trailing-return-type,
  -readability-identifier-length,
  -readability-magic-numbers

# Why these are ENABLED:
#   bugprone-*           — likely-bug patterns (uninit, narrowing, dangling). Cheap, accurate.
#   clang-analyzer-*     — full data-flow static analysis. Catches things lints can't (e.g.
#                          use-after-free across branches). Distinct from the rest.
#   concurrency-*        — won't fire much on a single-threaded event loop, but free insurance.
#   cppcoreguidelines-*  — Bjarne/Herb's rules. Opinionated and educational — exactly what
#                          you want as a C++ learner. Several pro-* sub-checks are too strict
#                          for systems code; see disables below.
#   misc-*               — grab bag, includes useful ones like misc-include-cleaner and
#                          misc-const-correctness.
#   modernize-*          — pushes toward modern idioms (smart pointers, ranged-for, override,
#                          using-aliases over typedefs). Highly educational.
#   performance-*        — copy/move/string smells. Cheap signal.
#   portability-*        — Linux + macOS targets means this matters; flags
#                          implementation-defined behaviour.
#   readability-*        — clarity rules. Some overlap with clang-format (which handles
#                          whitespace); these handle structure (long functions, deep nesting,
#                          implicit bool conversions).
#
# Why these are DISABLED:
#   bugprone-easily-swappable-parameters
#       Fires on every function with two same-typed parameters: f(int x, int y), f(int w,
#       int h). Honest TUI / coordinate code is full of these. Too noisy, low yield.
#   cppcoreguidelines-avoid-magic-numbers / readability-magic-numbers
#       Fires on EVERY integer literal that isn't 0 or 1. In TUI code (column counts, key
#       codes, terminal escape sequences) this is unbearable. Re-enable later when you have
#       a better sense of where named constants actually help.
#   cppcoreguidelines-non-private-member-variables-in-classes /
#   misc-non-private-member-variables-in-classes
#       Both forbid public/protected data members. But `struct` is a legitimate C++ tool for
#       passive-data aggregates (POD types, MI-protocol record structs). The duplicate also
#       means double diagnostics if both stay on.
#   cppcoreguidelines-pro-bounds-array-to-pointer-decay
#       Fires on `assert(x)` and a bunch of legitimate C-string interop. Known false-positive
#       generator. The Core Guidelines themselves admit this rule is impractical without
#       gsl::span everywhere — and we're not pulling in GSL.
#   cppcoreguidelines-pro-bounds-pointer-arithmetic
#       Same problem: any C-string or buffer code lights up. Reach for std::span where it
#       fits, but don't have the linter scream at every char* loop.
#   misc-no-recursion
#       Recursion is a normal tool. AST walks, MI-record parsing, tree rendering — all
#       naturally recursive. The check is over-broad.
#   modernize-use-trailing-return-type
#       `auto f() -> int` over `int f()`. Genuinely controversial; many seniors find it
#       harder to scan. Leave off unless you decide you like it.
#   readability-identifier-length
#       Forbids 1-character names. `for (int i = 0; ...)` is fine. Loop indices and short
#       lambda params don't need to be `index_counter`.

# WarningsAsErrors
# ----------------
# '*' promotes every enabled diagnostic to an error. This is the strict choice: no warning
# rot. The cost: any clang-tidy hit becomes a hard fail.
#
# Editor-vs-CI tension: if you wire this into CMAKE_CXX_CLANG_TIDY, every build fails on
# any warning, which is great for discipline but painful while iterating. Two ways out:
#   (1) Run clang-tidy only in CI / pre-commit (recommended for now).
#   (2) Keep WarningsAsErrors='*' here for CI, and run editor-time tidy through clangd's
#       --tidy-checks flag separately (clangd surfaces them as squiggles, not failures).
WarningsAsErrors: '*'

# HeaderFilterRegex
# -----------------
# clang-tidy lints every translation unit's headers it sees — INCLUDING system, vendored,
# and FetchContent'ed library headers. Without a filter, you'd be linting libstdc++ and
# ftxui's source. This regex restricts header diagnostics to files inside this project.
#
# How: clang-tidy applies the regex to the absolute path of each header. Negative
# lookahead (?!...) excludes anything whose path contains a build/ component. The trailing
# extension match limits to C/C++ header extensions.
#
# Adjust if you reorganise into src/ + include/ — at that point you can tighten this to
# `.*debug-plus/(src|include|tests)/.*\.(h|hpp)$` for an even narrower allowlist.
HeaderFilterRegex: '.*debug-plus/(?!build/).*\.(h|hh|hpp|hxx)$'

# FormatStyle
# -----------
# Lets clang-tidy auto-fixes use your .clang-format style instead of LLVM defaults. Means
# `clang-tidy --fix` produces patches that match the rest of your code.
FormatStyle: file

# CheckOptions
# ------------
# Per-check tuning. The big ones:
#   - readability-identifier-naming enforces a naming scheme. The settings below match
#     Google's C++ style (consistent with BasedOnStyle: Google in .clang-format):
#       * Types (class/struct/enum/alias):  CamelCase
#       * Functions / methods:              CamelCase  (Google convention; flip to camelBack
#                                                       if you'd rather)
#       * Variables / parameters:           lower_case
#       * Private member variables:         lower_case_   (trailing underscore)
#       * Constants and constexpr:          kCamelCase
#       * Enum constants:                   kCamelCase
#       * Namespaces:                       lower_case
#       * Macros:                           UPPER_CASE
#       * Template parameters:              CamelCase
#
#   - readability-function-size and readability-function-cognitive-complexity bound how
#     gnarly a single function is allowed to be. Defaults are too lenient; the values below
#     are strict-but-shippable.
#
#   - modernize-use-auto.MinTypeNameLength=5 keeps `int i = 0` from being rewritten to
#     `auto i = 0` while still pushing for `auto` on long iterator/template types.
CheckOptions:
  # ---- Naming ----
  - { key: readability-identifier-naming.ClassCase,                value: CamelCase }
  - { key: readability-identifier-naming.StructCase,               value: CamelCase }
  - { key: readability-identifier-naming.EnumCase,                 value: CamelCase }
  - { key: readability-identifier-naming.UnionCase,                value: CamelCase }
  - { key: readability-identifier-naming.TypeAliasCase,            value: CamelCase }
  - { key: readability-identifier-naming.TypedefCase,              value: CamelCase }
  - { key: readability-identifier-naming.TemplateParameterCase,    value: CamelCase }

  - { key: readability-identifier-naming.FunctionCase,             value: CamelCase }
  - { key: readability-identifier-naming.MethodCase,               value: CamelCase }

  - { key: readability-identifier-naming.VariableCase,             value: lower_case }
  - { key: readability-identifier-naming.ParameterCase,            value: lower_case }
  - { key: readability-identifier-naming.LocalVariableCase,        value: lower_case }

  - { key: readability-identifier-naming.MemberCase,               value: lower_case }
  - { key: readability-identifier-naming.PrivateMemberCase,        value: lower_case }
  - { key: readability-identifier-naming.PrivateMemberPrefix,      value: '_' }
  - { key: readability-identifier-naming.ProtectedMemberCase,      value: lower_case }
  - { key: readability-identifier-naming.ProtectedMemberPrefix,    value: '_' }
  - { key: readability-identifier-naming.PublicMemberCase,         value: lower_case }

  - { key: readability-identifier-naming.ConstexprVariableCase,    value: CamelCase }
  - { key: readability-identifier-naming.ConstexprVariablePrefix,  value: 'k' }
  - { key: readability-identifier-naming.GlobalConstantCase,       value: CamelCase }
  - { key: readability-identifier-naming.GlobalConstantPrefix,     value: 'k' }
  - { key: readability-identifier-naming.StaticConstantCase,       value: CamelCase }
  - { key: readability-identifier-naming.StaticConstantPrefix,     value: 'k' }
  - { key: readability-identifier-naming.EnumConstantCase,         value: CamelCase }
  - { key: readability-identifier-naming.EnumConstantPrefix,       value: 'k' }

  - { key: readability-identifier-naming.NamespaceCase,            value: lower_case }
  - { key: readability-identifier-naming.MacroDefinitionCase,      value: UPPER_CASE }

  # ---- Complexity bounds ----
  # Cognitive complexity = a structured measure of how hard a function is to follow.
  # Default 25 is generous; 20 forces splitting genuinely tangled functions.
  - { key: readability-function-cognitive-complexity.Threshold,    value: '20' }

  # Function-size thresholds. Each threshold can fire independently.
  - { key: readability-function-size.LineThreshold,                value: '80' }
  - { key: readability-function-size.StatementThreshold,           value: '50' }
  - { key: readability-function-size.BranchThreshold,              value: '10' }
  - { key: readability-function-size.ParameterThreshold,           value: '5' }
  - { key: readability-function-size.NestingThreshold,             value: '4' }
  - { key: readability-function-size.VariableThreshold,            value: '15' }

  # ---- modernize tuning ----
  # Don't rewrite `int i = 0` to `auto i = 0` — auto only earns its keep on longer types.
  - { key: modernize-use-auto.MinTypeNameLength,                   value: '5' }
  # Prefer `= default` and `= delete` over hand-written empty bodies.
  - { key: modernize-use-equals-default.IgnoreMacros,              value: 'true' }

  # ---- bugprone tuning ----
  # Let assertions side-effect freely (assert(read(fd, buf, n) == n)). Matters for tests.
  - { key: bugprone-assert-side-effect.AssertMacros,
      value: 'assert,NSAssert,NSCAssert' }

  # ---- readability tuning ----
  # Forbid implicit int-to-bool: `if (n)` becomes `if (n != 0)`. Catches a real category
  # of bugs (forgetting to compare).
  - { key: readability-implicit-bool-conversion.AllowIntegerConditions, value: 'false' }
  - { key: readability-implicit-bool-conversion.AllowPointerConditions, value: 'false' }
